so a missing or mis-ordered layer is an error rather than a silently wrong
result. Only bare layer names combined with \code{+} are supported, such as
\code{prec ~ elev + slope}. Transformations (\code{log(elev)}), interactions
(\code{elev:slope}), and \code{.} are rejected; create the derived layer first.

In the common case there is one coarse response and a fine predictor such as a
digital elevation model, and no coarse predictor in hand. A predictor named in
the formula but absent from \code{data} is then derived by aggregating its \code{onto}
layer to the response grid with \code{aggregate}, so \code{topocast(prec ~ elev, data = prec_coarse, onto = dem_fine, radius = 15)} works directly from a coarse
climate layer and a fine DEM.

Several responses that share the predictors are downscaled together by naming
them as \code{cbind(prec, tmin) ~ elev}. The moving-window design depends only on the
predictors, so it is fit once and solved against every response; the result has
one layer (or column) per response. With \code{coefficients} or \code{diagnostics}, the
extra grids are prefixed by the response name. The setup a call does around the
fit is shared the same way: the coefficient grids reach \code{onto} in one
resampling step and the \code{onto} predictors are read once for the call. Responses
on one coarse grid sharing one \code{onto}, such as several climate scenarios
downscaled onto the same range, therefore cost less named together in one call
than split across several.

